<font color="#FF0000">FEEDBACK TO JULIA</font><br>
<tt>Tue Apr  8  1:55:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Julia,<br><br>
I left DaNang, Vietnam in June of 1971 after having lobbied for months to get an early out off an extension in my enlistment.  I had extended my enlistment to go there as a USAF pararescueman.  Now, I was coming home.<br><br>
The stewardesses were very nice to us, but I don't remember much about the trip back. I did sleep a lot.<br><br>
I do remember protesters at a gate we had to pass through, saying the usual things, and there was some spitting. But I don't remember clearly beyond that (perhaps I don't want to remember). <br><br>
I also went back to school, and remember a news clip that went by so quickly that I didn't get it all--a rescue chopper had been downed by enemy fire, and nobody cared.  Service buddies of mine were dead, and no one it the college co-op except another service buddy who had served with me cared.  It was weird.<br><br>
I think that the most upsetting to me was the indifference.  There are several other stories, but it is late and I am tired, so maybe another time.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


